In article <1992Apr03.020642.158822@cs.cmu.edu> mnr+@cs.cmu.edu (Marc Ringuette) writes:
>> ...Each 7 seconds a
>> new key is simultaneously adopted by all of the securcoms on the
>> network...The adoption of this new key does not involve transmitting the
>> key on the network at all....
>Various people have noticed that you can get very accurate little
>quartz clocks that will stay in sync.  Maybe they do some sort of
>time-based encryption to generate a new key each 7 seconds.
>The boxes would still have to "share a secret" in order to be secure...
>but presumably the secret meta-key is installed in the factory, and
>the 7-second session keys are generated using some sort of
>cryptographically secure means, such as DES'ing the current time
>using the meta-key to create a 7-second key.

Which mean what they actually got is a single key system where the key
never changes.  Yet another Security through Obscurity scheme.  The 
flaws in the system are obvious.  I wonder how they protect the meta-key,
thermite in the chip? :-)

